<h3>Cooperating FID</h3>

<p>As Specialized Information Service (FID) for Criminology, we collaborate with other Specialized Information Services. In particular, we work closely with the FID Theology and the FID Religious Studies, both of which are also based at the University Library Tübingen. Together, we form the “FID Department.” This collaboration includes the development of shared workflows, the exchange of expertise, regular coordination, and mutual support in funding applications and other cross-departmental tasks.</p>
<p>In the technical domain, all three FIDs benefit from a shared infrastructure based on VuFind. Developments, security measures, and technical enhancements are centrally coordinated and rolled out to all systems. Pooling the expertise of the technical staff enables efficient processes.</p>
<p>In addition, the FID Criminology is a (founding) member of the Germany-wide FID network <a target="_blank" href="https://wikis.sub.uni-hamburg.de/webis/index.php/FID-Netzwerk_für_Rechts-,_Wirtschafts-_und_Sozialwissenschaften_/_REWISO%2B">REWISO+</a>, the. The REWISO+ network brings together a diverse range of disciplines and areas of work to strengthen the overall system of Specialized Information Services for academia at multiple levels. Key areas of collaboration include acquisition and <span style="text-decoration: underline;">licensing</span>, the <span style="text-decoration: underline;">transformation toward Open Access</span>, and <span style="text-decoration: underline;">public outreach</span>. During working meetings held three to four times a year, network members exchange views on current FID-related topics. Other meetings, open to additional FIDs, are held at irregular intervals on various topics, such as “user feedback.” Furthermore, REWISO+ maintains an ongoing dialogue with the NFDI consortia Text+, SWD, and BERD.</p>
<p>The FID Criminology continuously seeks further collaborations to provide users with a broad spectrum of subject-specific information and resources.</p>

